STUDENT PERFORMANCE PREDICTION PROJECT DEMO STEPS

Project Demo Plan:
I will first show the deployed project on AWS Elastic Beanstalk because the rubric requires cloud deployment and UI.
Then I will briefly show that the project is containerized using Docker.
If AWS or Docker fails, I will use the local FastAPI server as backup.

--------------------------------------------------
PART 1: AWS ELASTIC BEANSTALK DEMO
--------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
This is the main demo because the application is deployed on the cloud using AWS Elastic Beanstalk.

Steps:

1. Open AWS Academy / AWS Learner Lab.
2. Start the lab.
3. Open AWS Console.
4. Go to Elastic Beanstalk.
5. Select the same region where the environment was created.
   Example:
   us-east-1

6. Open the environment:
   student-performance-env

7. Wait until the environment health becomes:
   Ok

8. Open the Elastic Beanstalk public URL.
   Example:
   http://student-performance-env.eba-xxxx.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com/

9. Expected output:
   {"message":"Student Performance Prediction API is running"}

10. Open Swagger UI by adding /docs at the end of the same URL:
   http://student-performance-env.eba-xxxx.us-east-1.elasticbeanstalk.com/docs

11. Click:
   POST /predict

12. Click:
   Try it out

13. Paste this sample JSON:

{
  "study_hours_per_day": 4,
  "attendance_percentage": 85,
  "mental_health_rating": 7,
  "sleep_hours": 7,
  "social_media_hours": 2,
  "netflix_hours": 1,
  "exercise_frequency": 3,
  "part_time_job": 0,
  "gender": 1,
  "diet_quality": 2,
  "internet_quality": 1,
  "extracurricular_participation": 1
}

14. Click:
   Execute

15. Expected output:
   predicted_exam_score
   model_used


--------------------------------------------------
PART 2: DOCKER LOCAL DEMO
--------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
This shows that the project is containerized and can run in the same environment on any machine.

Step 1: Open Docker Desktop.
Wait until Docker Desktop is running.

Step 2: Open terminal in the project folder where these files exist:
app.py
best_model.pkl
Dockerfile
requirements.txt
student_habits_performance.csv
student_performance_prediction.py

Step 3: Check Docker version:

docker version

Step 4: Build Docker image:

docker build -t student-performance .

Step 5: Run Docker container:

docker run -p 5055:8080 student-performance

Note:
5055 is the laptop port.
8080 is the container port.

Step 6: Open in browser:

http://localhost:5055

Expected output:
{"message":"Student Performance Prediction API is running"}

Step 7: Open Swagger UI:

http://localhost:5055/docs

Step 8: Test POST /predict using the same JSON input.

If port 5055 is already in use, first check running containers:

docker ps

Stop old container:

docker stop CONTAINER_ID

Then run again:

docker run -p 5055:8080 student-performance

Docker packages the FastAPI app, trained model, dependencies, and runtime environment into one container. This avoids dependency issues and makes deployment easier.

--------------------------------------------------
PART 3: NORMAL LOCAL FASTAPI BACKUP
--------------------------------------------------

Purpose:
This is only a backup method if Docker or AWS does not work.

Step 1: Open terminal in the project folder.

Step 2: Create virtual environment:

python -m venv venv

Step 3: Activate virtual environment on Windows:

venv\Scripts\activate

Step 4: Install requirements:

pip install -r requirements.txt

Step 5: Run FastAPI app:

uvicorn app:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8080 --reload

Step 6: Open in browser:

http://localhost:8080

Expected output:
{"message":"Student Performance Prediction API is running"}

Step 7: Open Swagger UI:

http://localhost:8080/docs

Step 8: Test POST /predict using the same JSON input.

--------------------------------------------------
IMPORTANT DEMO TALKING POINTS
--------------------------------------------------

1. Dataset:
The dataset is student_habits_performance.csv. It contains student academic and lifestyle features. The target variable is exam_score.

2. Problem type:
This is a supervised regression problem because the model predicts a continuous exam score.

3. Features used:
study_hours_per_day
attendance_percentage
mental_health_rating
sleep_hours
social_media_hours
netflix_hours
exercise_frequency
part_time_job
gender
diet_quality
internet_quality
extracurricular_participation

4. Models trained:
Linear Regression
Decision Tree Regressor
Random Forest Regressor

5. Model selection:
The best model was selected using the lowest RMSE on the test set.

6. Evaluation metrics:
RMSE
MAE
R2 score

7. Why RMSE:
RMSE was used because it measures prediction error for a regression problem and penalizes large errors more strongly.

8. Docker purpose:
Docker containerizes the application so it can run consistently on different systems.

9. Beanstalk purpose:
AWS Elastic Beanstalk hosts the Dockerized application on the cloud and provides a public URL.

10. Prediction endpoint:
The /predict endpoint receives student feature values as JSON, sends them to the trained model, and returns the predicted exam score.
